      = [https://www.law.upenn.edu/live/files/5191-aba-509 \"Penn Law Profile\"]\n| logo                  =\n| logo_size             =\n| logo_alt              =\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Pennsylvania Carey Law School''' (formerly the '''University of Pennsylvania Law School''', sometimes shortened to '''Penn Law''', '''UPenn Law''', or '''Penn Carey Law''') is the law school of the [[University of Pennsylvania]], an [[Ivy League law schools|Ivy League]] university located in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].  It is among the most selective and oldest law schools in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/default/files/biblio/1002/145871/doc/slspublic/lomio_etal-rp20.pdf|title=Ranking of Top Law Schools 1987-2009 by US News & World Report|author1=J. Paul Lomio |author2=Erika V. Wayne |author3=George D. Wilson |last-author-amp=yes |date=July 5, 2016|work=US News & World Report|access-date=5 July 2016}}</ref> and is currently ranked 7th overall by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings |title=Best Law Schools |work=US News & World Report|date= |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> It offers the degrees of [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.), [[Master of Laws]] (LL.M.), Master of Comparative Laws (LL.C.M.), Master in Law (M.L.), and [[Doctor of Juridical Science|Doctor of the Science of Law]] (S.J.D.).\n\nThe entering class typically consists of approximately 250 students, and admission is highly competitive.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[https://www.law.upenn.edu/admissions/jd/entering-class-profile.php Admissions: Entering Class Profile \u2022 Penn Law<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Penn Law's July 2018 weighted first-time bar passage rate was 92.09%.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The law school is one of the [[Law school rankings in the United States#Top 14 law schools|\"T14\" law schools]], that is, schools that have consistently ranked within the top 14 law schools since ''U.S. News & World Report'' began publishing rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prelawhandbook.com/law_school_rankings__1987_1999 |title=Prelaw Handbook Historical US News Rankings |publisher=PRELAWHANDBOOK |date= |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> In the class entering in 2018, over half of students were women, over a third identified as persons of color, and 10% of students enrolled with an advanced degree.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nThe law school offers an extensive curriculum and hosts various student groups, research centers, and activities. Students publish the ''[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]]'', the oldest law journal in the country.<ref name=Almanac>[http://www.upenn.edu/almanac/v47/n12/LawTimeline.html \"University of Pennsylvania Law School Sesquicentennial History\"], University of Pennsylvania Almanac, accessed 15 Sep 2011</ref> Students also publish ''[[The Regulatory Review]]'', a regulatory news, analysis, and commentary that publishes daily.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=https://www.theregreview.org/about-us/|website=The Regulatory Review|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref> Among the school's alumni are a US Supreme Court Justice, several state Supreme Court Justices and supreme court justices of foreign countries, as well as several founders of law firms, university presidents and deans, business entrepreneurs, and politicians.\n\nBased on student survey responses, [[American Bar Association|ABA]], and [[NALP]] data, 99.2% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time employment after graduation, with a median salary of $180,000, as 76% of students joined law firms and 11% obtained judicial clerkships.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://www.law.upenn.edu/careers/employment-statistics.php Careers: Employment Statistics \u2022 Penn Law<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The law school was ranked # 2 of all law schools nationwide by the ''[[National Law Journal]]'' in terms of sending the highest percentage of 2018 graduates to the 100 largest law firms in the US (60%).<ref name=\"nationallawjournal.com\">[https://www.law.com/2019/03/07/and-no-1-on-this-years-go-to-law-school-is/ \"Ranking The Go-To Law Schools,\" ''National Law Journal''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lewis 5333429670 112607c0ef o.jpg|thumb|180px|[[William Draper Lewis]], Penn Law's Dean, and founder of the [[American Law Institute]]]]\nThe University of Pennsylvania Law School, later University of Pennsylvania Carey Law School, traces its origins to a series of lectures delivered, in 1790, by [[James Wilson (justice)|James Wilson]], a signer of the [[United States Declaration of Independence]] and the [[United States Constitution]].<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/about/history/ |title=History of Penn Law |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> Penn began offering a full-time program in law in 1850, under the leadership of [[George Sharswood]].<ref name=\"history\" /> In 1852, Penn was the first law school in the nation to publish a law journal still in existence, then called ''The American Law Register'', which was later renamed the ''[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]]'', one of the most-cited law journals in the world.<ref name=\"lawlib.wlu.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://lawlib.wlu.edu/LJ/index.aspx|title=Law Journals: Submissions and Ranking|work=wlu.edu|access-date=2017-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060307221833/http://lawlib.wlu.edu/LJ/index.aspx|archive-date=2006-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis_Pollak.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Louis H. Pollak]], Dean and later a judge of the  [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania|US District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania]].]]\nIn 1881 the first woman was admitted to the school, [[Carrie Burnham Kilgore]], and in 1888 the first African American man graduated from the school, [[Aaron Albert Mossell]].<ref>[https://www.law.upenn.edu/about/history.php About: History \u2022 Penn Law<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[William Draper Lewis]] was named dean in 1896.<ref name=\"Almanac\"/> In 1900, the Trustees of the University of Pennsylvania approved a move to the law school's current location at the intersection of 34th and [[Chestnut Street (Philadelphia)|Chestnut Street]]s.<ref name=\"Owen Roberts 1949\">Owen Roberts, William Draper Lewis, 98 ''U. Pa. L. Rev.'' 1 (1949)</ref> Under Lewis' deanship, the law school was one of the first schools to emphasize legal teaching by full-time professors instead of practitioners, a system that is still followed today.<ref name=\"Owen Roberts 1949\"/> As legal education became more formalized, the school initiated a three-year curriculum and instituted stringent admissions requirements. While the School continued to accept students who did not hold a bachelor's degree, it warned applicants that \"[a] large number of those who study law are college graduates; and those who are not cannot hope, except in rare instances, to compete successfully with the college man.\"<ref>\"Department of Law,\" Catalogue of the University of Pennsylvania, 1899-1900 234 (1899).</ref>\n\nAfter 30 years with the law school, Lewis founded the [[American Law Institute]] in 1925, which was seated in the law school and was chaired by Lewis himself. The ALI was later chaired by another of Penn Law's Deans, [[Herbert Funk Goodrich]]. Two years before Goodrich was named dean, in 1927 the law school graduated with a J.D. [[Sadie Tanner Mossell Alexander]], who was the first African-American woman to ever receive a Ph.D. in the United States (also from the University of Pennsylvania, in economics).<ref name=Almanac/> The first woman to join the faculty was [[Martha Field]] in 1969; she is now a professor at [[Harvard Law School]].<ref name=Almanac/> From 1974 to 1978 the Dean of the law school was [[Louis Pollak]], who later became a federal judge.\n\nIn November 2019, Penn Law received a $125 million donation from the W.P. Carey Foundation, the largest single donation to any law school to date; the school was renamed University of Pennsylvania Carey Law School, in honor of the foundation's first president, Penn Law alumnus Francis J. Carey (1926-2014), who was the brother of [[William P. Carey|William Polk Carey]] (1930 - 2012), founder of the [[W. P. Carey|W. P. Carey Inc.]] [[REIT]], and of the charitable foundation.<ref>[https://www.thedp.com/article/2019/11/penn-law-carey-foundation-donation-renaming \"Penn Law renamed \u2018Carey Law School\u2019 following record $125 million donation\", by Manlu Liu, November 8, 2019. Retrieved November 17, 2019.]</ref><ref>[https://penntoday.upenn.edu/news/w-p-carey-foundation-makes-historic-125-million-gift-name-penns-law-school \"W. P. Carey Foundation makes historic $125 million gift to name Penn\u2019s law school\", by Steven Barnes, ''PennToday'', Office of University Communications, November 8, 2019. Retrieved November 17, 2019.]</ref> The change was met by some controversy, and a petition to quash the abbreviated \"Carey Law\", in favor of the traditional \"Penn Law\", was circulated.\n<ref>[http://www.nationaljurist.com/national-jurist-magazine/penn-laws-name-change-honor-big-donor-causing-outcry 'Penn Law's name change in honor of big donor is causing outcry\", by Mike Stetz, ''The National Jurist'']</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:University of Pennsylvania Law School-angled.JPG|300px|thumb|Silverman Hall]]\nThe University of Pennsylvania campus covers over 269 acres (~1&nbsp;km\u00b2) in a contiguous area of [[West Philadelphia]]'s [[University City, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|University City]] district. All of Penn's schools, including the law school, and most of its research institutes are located on this campus. Much of Penn's architecture was designed by the architecture firm of [[Cope & Stewardson]], whose principal architects combined the [[Gothic architecture]] of the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of Cambridge]] with the local landscape to establish the [[Collegiate Gothic]] style.\n\nThe law school consists of four interconnecting buildings around a central [[courtyard]].  At the east end of the courtyard is Silverman Hall, built in 1900, housing the Levy Conference Center, classrooms, faculty offices, the Gittis Center for Clinical Legal Studies, and administrative and student offices. Directly opposite is Tanenbaum Hall, home to the Biddle Law Library several law journals, administrative offices, and student spaces. The law library houses 1,053,824 volumes and volume equivalents making it the 4th-largest law library in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/university-of-pennsylvania-03140|title=University of Pennsylvania|work=rankingsandreviews.com}}</ref> Gittis Hall sits on the north side and has new classrooms (renovated in 2006) and new and expanded faculty offices.  Opposite is Golkin Hall, which contains {{convert|40000|sqft|m2}} and includes a state-of-the-art court room, 350-seat auditorium, seminar rooms, faculty and administrative offices, a two-story entry hall, and a roof-top garden.\n\nA small row of restaurants and shops faces the law school on Sansom Street.  Nearby are the Penn Bookstore, the Pottruck Center (a {{convert|115000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} multi-purpose sports activity area), the Institute of Contemporary Art, a performing arts center, and area shops.\n\n==Academics==\n\n===School orientation===\nFor the class entering in the fall of 2018, 14.6% out of 6,483 applicants were offered admission, with 249 matriculating. For the class entering in 2018 the 25th and 75th [[LSAT]] percentiles for the entering class were 164 and 171, respectively, with a median of 170.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> The 25th and 75th undergraduate [[GPA]] percentiles were 3.49 and 3.95, respectively, with a median of 3.89.<ref>https://www.law.upenn.edu/admissions/jd/entering-class-profile.php</ref><ref>https://www.ilrg.com/rankings/law/1/desc/Employ9Mos?name=&state=</ref>\n\nThroughout its modern history, Penn has been known for its strong focus on inter-disciplinary studies, a character that was shaped early on by Dean [[William Draper Lewis]].<ref>[[Margaret Center Klingelsmith]], \"History of the Department of Law of the University of Pennsylvania,\" The Proceedings at the Dediction of the New Building of the Department of Law, February 21st and 22nd, 1900, 16-18 (George Erasmus Nitzsche, comp. 1901).</ref> Its medium-size student body and the tight integration with the rest of Penn's schools (the \"One University Policy\")<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archives.upenn.edu/primdocs/uplan/paoneuniv1972.pdf |title=Pennsylvania: One University |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Archives |year=1973 |accessdate=2011-09-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128081440/http://www.archives.upenn.edu/primdocs/uplan/paoneuniv1972.pdf |archive-date=2012-01-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> have been instrumental in achieving that aim. More than 50% of the law school's courses are interdisciplinary, and it offers more than 20 joint and dual degree programs, including a JD/MBA ([[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]]), a JD/PhD in Communication ([[Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania]]), and a JD/MD ([[Perelman School of Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania|Perelman School of Medicine]]).\n\nVarious certificate programs that can be completed within the 3-year JD program are also available, e.g. in Business and Public Policy (in conjunction with the [[Wharton School]]), in Cross-Sector Innovation (with the School of Social Policy & Practice), in International Business and Law (the Themis Joint Certificate with ESADE Law School, Barcelona, Spain), and in Social Cognitive and Affective Neuroscience (SCAN).<ref>{{cite web |title=SCAN Certificate helps law students use neuroscience to understand human behavior |url=https://www.law.upenn.edu/live/news/5382-scan-certificate-helps-law-students-use |website=Penn Law}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Graduate Certificate in Social, Cognitive & Affective Neuroscience (SCAN) |url=https://neuroethics.upenn.edu/scan/ |website=Center for Neuroscience and Society}}</ref> Nineteen percent of the Class of 2007 earned a Certificate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/crossdisc/study/certificates/ |title=Penn Law&nbsp;\u2013 Certificates of Study |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525174504/http://www.law.upenn.edu/crossdisc/study/certificates/ |archive-date=May 25, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Penn Law also offers joint degrees with international affiliates such as [[Sciences Po]] (France), [[ESADE]] (Spain), and the [[University of Hong Kong Faculty of Law]]. Under the guidance of former Dean Michael A. Fitts, the School has further expanded its international programs with the addition of the International Internship Program, the International Summer Human Rights Program, and the Global Research Seminar, all under the umbrella of the Penn Law Global Initiative. Penn Law takes part in a number of international annual events, such as the [[Monroe E. Price Media Law Moot Court Competition]] at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 International Rounds in Oxford&nbsp;\u2013 Results|url=http://pricemootcourt.socleg.ox.ac.uk/competitions/oxford/2011/results|publisher=University of Oxford&nbsp;\u2013 Price Media Law Moot Court Programme|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Career prospects===\nPenn combines a strong tradition in public service with being one of the top feeders of law students to the most prestigious law firms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202483173162&slreturn=1&hbxlogin=1|title=LAW SCHOOLS REPORT|work=National Law Journal}}</ref> Penn Law was the first top-ranked law school to establish a mandatory pro bono requirement, and the first law school to win American Bar Association's Pro Bono Publico Award. Nevertheless, still about 75% of each graduating class enters private practice. In 2012, the law school placed more than 60% of its graduates into the United States' top 250 law firms, maintaining Penn's rank as the number one law school in the nation for the percentage of students securing employment at these top law firms.<ref name=\"National Law Journal law.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?interactive=true&id=1202543436520 |title=Ranking The Go-To Law Schools |work=National Law Journal|date= |accessdate= February 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202589189668&interactive=true National Law Journal law.com. Retrieved August 12, 2013.]</ref>\n\n===Journals===\nStudents at the law school publish several legal journals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/prospective/studentactivities.html |title=List of Student Activities |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525172052/http://www.law.upenn.edu/prospective/studentactivities.html |archive-date=May 25, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The flagship publication is the ''[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]]'', the oldest [[law review]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pennumbra.com|title=University of Pennsylvania Law Review - PennLawReview.com|work=pennumbra.com}}</ref> Penn Law Review started in 1852 as the ''American Law Register'', and was renamed to its current title in 1908.<ref name=Almanac/> It is one of the most-cited law journals in the world,<ref name=\"lawlib.wlu.edu\"/> and one of the four journals that are responsible for ''[[The Bluebook]]'' (along with the Harvard, Yale, and Columbia law journals). ''Penn Law Review'' articles have captured seminal historical moments in the 19th and 20th century, such as the passage of the [[19th Amendment to the United States Constitution|19th Amendment]], the lawlessness of the first and second [[World War]], the rise of the civil rights movement, and the war in Vietnam.<ref>Edwin J. Greenlee, The University of Pennsylvania Law Review: 150 Years of History, 150 ''U. Pa. L. Rev.'' 1875 (2002)</ref>\n\nOther law journals include:\n*''[[University of Pennsylvania Journal of Constitutional Law]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pennjcl.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126053840/http://www.pennjcl.com/ |archive-date=2012-11-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> one of the top 50 law journals in the United States based on citations and impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lawlib.wlu.edu/LJ/index.aspx |title=Law Journals: Submissions and Ranking |publisher=Lawlib.wlu.edu |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060307221833/http://lawlib.wlu.edu/LJ/index.aspx |archive-date=March 7, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*''[[University of Pennsylvania Journal of International Law]]'', f/k/a ''Journal of International Economic Law'', f/k/a ''Journal of International Business Law'', f/k/a ''Journal of Comparative Business and Capital Market Law''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pennjil.com |title=The Journal of International Law |publisher=Pennjil.com |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n*''[[University of Pennsylvania Journal of Business Law]]'', f/k/a ''Journal of Business and Employment Law''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/journals/jbl/ |title=The University of Pennsylvania Journal of Business Law |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date=November 12, 2010 |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n*''[[University of Pennsylvania Journal of Law and Social Change]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/journals/jlasc/ |title=The Journal of Law and Social Change |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n*''[[East Asia Law Review]]'', f/k/a ''Chinese Law and Policy Review''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pennealr.com |title=East Asia Law Review&nbsp;\u2013 Journal of Law and Practice in East Asian Nations Including China, Japan, Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Macau, Tibet |publisher=Pennealr.com |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121165128/http://www.pennealr.com/ |archive-date=November 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==U.S. Supreme Court clerkships==\nSince 2000, Penn has had [[List of law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States|seven alumni]] serve as judicial clerks at the [[U.S. Supreme Court]]. This record gives Penn a ranking of 10th among all law schools for supplying such law clerks for the period 2000-2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bcgsearch.com/article/900047770/Law-Schools-That-Send-the-Most-Attorneys-to-United-States-Supreme-Court-Clerkships/ |title=Law Schools That Send the Most Attorneys to United States Supreme Court Clerkships |publisher=BCGSearch.com |date=2014-12-05 |accessdate=2019-11-29}}</ref> Penn has placed [[List of law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States|48 clerks]] at the U.S. Supreme Court in its history, ranked 11th among law schools; this group includes [[Curtis R. Reitz]], who is the [[Algernon Sydney Biddle]] Professor of Law, Emeritus at Penn.\n\n==Employment==\nBased on student survey responses, [[American Bar Association|ABA]], and [[NALP]] data, 99.2% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time employment after graduation, with a median salary of $180,000, as 76% of students joined law firms and 11% obtained judicial clerkships.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nThe law school was ranked # 2 of all law schools nationwide by the ''[[National Law Journal]]'' in terms of sending the highest percentage of 2018 graduates to the largest 100 law firms in the US (60%).<ref name=\"nationallawjournal.com\"/>\n\n==Costs==\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition ($61,608), fees, and living expenses) for the 2018-2019 academic year was $95,400.<ref>[https://www.law.upenn.edu/admissions/grad/tuition-fees.php Graduate Programs: Tuition & Fees \u2022 Penn Law<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{main|List of Penn Law School alumni}}\n\n[[File:Jowenroberts.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Owen Roberts]], U.S. Supreme Court Justice]]\n\n===Judiciary===\n* [[Owen Roberts]], U.S. Supreme Court Justice \n* [[James Harry Covington]], Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]] \n* [[Daniel John Layton]], Chief Justice of the [[Delaware Supreme Court]] \n* [[Robert Nelson Cornelius Nix, Jr.]], Chief Justice of the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]]\n* [[Horace Stern]], Chief Justice of the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]]\n* [[George Sharswood]], Chief Justice of the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]]\n* [[Deborah Tobias Poritz]], Chief Justice of the [[New Jersey Supreme Court]]\n* [[Ayala Procaccia]], Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Israel]] \n* [[Ronald Wilson]], Justice of the [[High Court of Australia]]\n* [[Yvonne Mokgoro]], Justice of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]]\n* Jasper Yeates Brinton, the architect of the Egyptian court system, Justice of the Egyptian Supreme Court, and former U.S. Legal Advisor to Egypt \n* [[Arlin Adams]], Circuit Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Max Rosenn]], Circuit Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Dolores Sloviter]], Circut Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[James Hunter III]], Circut Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Patty Shwartz]], Circuit Judge of the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Phyllis Kravitch]], Senior Circuit Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]]\n* [[Helene N. White]], Circuit judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]\n* [[Gerard Hogan]], Justice of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal of Ireland]]\n\n===Government===\n* [[George W. Wickersham]], Attorney General of the United States, 1909\u20131913; instrumental in the breakup of [[Standard Oil]]; President of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] (1933\u201336)<ref>{{cite web|title=George W. Wickersham|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/384/000167880/|publisher=Notable Names Data Base|accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Philip Werner Amram]], Asst. Attorney General of the United States, 1939\u201342<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Emancipation: The Making of the Black Lawyer, 1844-1944|author1=Smith, J.C.|author2=Marshall, T.|date=1999|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press, Incorporated|isbn=9780812216851|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1lOIjQUG4aoC&pg=PA187|page=187|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Robert J. Walker]], U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, 1840\u201345<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert J. Walker|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000067|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[William M. Meredith]], U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, 1849\u201350\n*[[Jay Clayton (attorney)|Walter J. \"Jay\" Clayton III]], Chairman, U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, 2017\u2013present.<ref>https://www.sec.gov/news/press-release/2017-94</ref>\n* [[Josiah E. DuBois Jr.]], U.S. State Department official, instrumental in Holocaust rescue<ref name=\"google4\">{{cite book|title=Blowing the Whistle on Genocide: Josiah E. Dubois Jr., and the Struggle for a U.S. Response to the Holocaust|author1=Medoff, R.|author2=Wyman, D.S.|author3=Eizenstat, S.|author4=Morgenthau, H.|date=2009|publisher=Purdue University|isbn=9781557535078|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yV7taankpswC&pg=PA2|page=2|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas K. Finletter]], U.S Secretary of the Air Force, 1950\u20131953; Ambassador to NATO, 1961\u201365<ref name=\"google5\">{{cite book|title=Secretaries and chiefs of staff of the United States Air Force|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=9781428990463|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qLM3IGCLkywC&pg=PA19|page=19|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lindley Miller Garrison]], U.S. Secretary of War, 1913\u201316<ref name=\"google6\">{{cite book|title=The United States in the First World War: An Encyclopedia|author1=Venzon, A.C.|author2=Miles, P.L.|date=1999|publisher=Garland Pub.|isbn=9780815333531|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YiZRC8bsOuoC&pg=PA250|page=250|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[William B. Gray]], United States Attorney for Vermont, 1977-1981<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hr1964.org/obits.htm#Gray |title=Class of 1964 Obituaries: William Barton Gray |date=1994 |website=HR 1964.org |publisher=Harvard-Radcliffe Class of 1964 |location=Cambridge, MA |access-date=November 16, 2019 |ref={{sfnRef|\"Class of 1964 Obituaries: William Barton Gray\"}}}}</ref>\n* [[Earl G. Harrison]], Commissioner of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service, 1942\u201344{{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n* [[George Washington Woodruff]], Acting U.S. Secretary of the Interior under President Theodore Roosevelt<ref>{{cite web|title=George Washington Woodruff|url=http://www.archives.upenn.edu/people/1800s/woodruff_geo_w.html|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|accessdate=January 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423201641/http://www.archives.upenn.edu/people/1800s/woodruff_geo_w.html|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Heath Tarbert]] Nominee for Assistant Secretary of the Treasury for International Markets and Development in the U.S. (2017)<ref>https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/04/04/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-heath-p-tarbert</ref>\n* [[William H. Brown, III]], Chairman, [[EEOC]]<ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=National Journal|author1=Government Research Corporation|author2=Center for Political Research|author3=Government Research Company|date=1971|volume=3|publisher=Government Research Corporation|issn=0360-4217|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zLZVAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Gilbert F. Casellas]], Chairman, [[EEOC]] and [[General Counsel of the Air Force]]<ref>{{cite web|title=GILBERT F. CASELLAS|url=http://www.eeoc.gov/eeoc/history/35th/bios/gilcasellas.html|website=eeoc.gov|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph Sill Clark]], U.S. Senator from Pennsylvania and Mayor of Philadelphia\n* [[Charles Robert Miller]], Governor of Delaware \n* [[Charles A. Heimbold, Jr.]], U.S. Ambassador to Sweden and former Chairman and CEO of [[Bristol-Myers Squibb Company]]  \n* [[Raul Roco]], former presidential candidate and Secretary of Education in the Philippines \n* [[Oscar Goodman]], Mayor of [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]\n* [[Harry Arista Mackey]], Mayor of Philadelphia\n* [[Martin J. Silverstein]], U.S. Ambassador to Uruguay \n* [[Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky]], member of the U.S. House of Representatives and women's rights activist\n\n===Academia===\n* [[Mark Yudof]], President of the [[University of California]] system\n* [[Peter J. Liacouras]], Chancellor of [[Temple University]]\n* [[John Frederick Zeller III]], President of [[Bucknell University]]\n* [[Rodney K. Smith]], President of [[Southern Virginia University]]\n* [[Janice R. Bellace]], first president of Singapore Management University\n* [[Fred Hilmer]], Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of New South Wales]] \n* [[Robert Butkin]], Dean of the [[University of Tulsa College of Law]]\n* [[William Schnader]], drafter of the [[Uniform Commercial Code]] \n* [[William Draper Lewis]], founder of the [[American Law Institute]] and Dean of Penn Law\n* [[Henry Martyn Hoyt, Jr.]], [[Solicitor General of the United States]]\n* [[E. Grey Lewis]], General Counsel of the [[U.S. Navy]]\n* [[Anthony Amsterdam]], professor at [[New York University School of Law]]\n* [[Khaled Abou El Fadl]], professor of law at [[UCLA School of Law]]\n* [[Curtis Reitz]], the Algernon Sydney Biddle Professor of Law at the University of Pennsylvania Law School \n* [[Caroline Burnham Kilgore]], Penn Law's first female graduate (1883) \n* [[Sadie Tanner Mossell Alexander]], the first African-American woman to receive a Ph.D. in the U.S. and graduated from Penn Law in 1927\n\n===Private Practice===\n* [[James Harry Covington]], co-founder of international law firm [[Covington & Burling]]\n* [[George Wharton Pepper]], U.S. Senator from Pennsylvania, and founder of national law firm [[Pepper Hamilton]]\n* Russell Duane, co-founder of international law firm [[Duane Morris]] \n* Stephen Cozen, co-founder of international law firm [[Cozen O'Connor]]\n\n===Business===\n* [[Safra Catz]], CEO of [[Oracle Corporation]]\n* [[Henry Silverman]], CEO of [[Cendant Corporation]] \n* [[Scott Mead]], partner and managing director of [[Goldman Sachs]]\n* [[Peter Detkin]], co-founder of [[Intellectual Ventures]] and former Vice-President and assistant general counsel at [[Intel]]\n* [[Paul G. Haaga, Jr.|Paul Haaga]], Chairman of Capital Research and Management Company of the [[Capital Group Companies]])\n* [[Sam Hamadeh]], founder of [[Vault.com]]\n* [[Edward Benjamin Shils]], professor and founder of the first research center for entrepreneurial studies in the world, at the Wharton School\n* [[David L. Cohen]], former Chief of Staff to Philadelphia Mayor [[Ed Rendell]]\n* [[Gigi Sohn]], founder and President of [[Public Knowledge]]\n\n===Media and arts===\n* [[Renee Chenault-Fattah]], co-anchor of weekday edition of [[WCAU]] [[NBC]] 10 News in Philadelphia\n* [[Mark Haines]], host on [[CNBC]] television network \n* [[El McMeen]], guitarist \n* [[Norman Pearlstine]], editor-in-chief of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' \n* [[Lisa Scottoline]], author of [[legal thriller]]s\n* [[Moe Jaffe]], bandleader and songwriter\n* [[John Heisman]], namesake of the [[Heisman Trophy]], graduated from the law school in 1892<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archives.upenn.edu/people/1800s/heisman_john.html|title=John Heisman (1869 - 1936)|work=upenn.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Notable faculty==\nThe law school's faculty is selected to match its inter-disciplinary orientation. Seventy percent of the standing faculty hold advanced degrees beyond the JD, and more than a third hold secondary appointments in other departments at the university. The law school is well known for its corporate law group, with professors [[Jill Fisch]], [[Charles W. Mooney Jr.|Charles (\"Chuck\") Mooney Jr.]], [[David Skeel]], and [[Michael Wachter]] being regularly included among the best corporate and securities law scholars in the country.<ref>[http://www.professorbainbridge.com/professorbainbridgecom/2011/05/corporate-practice-commentators-top-10-corporate-securities-articles-for-2010.html \"Corporate Practice Commentator's \"Top 10\" Corporate & Securities Articles for 2010\"]</ref> The School has also built a strong reputation for its law and economics group (professors [[Howard F. Chang]], [[Tom Baker (professor)|Tom Baker]]) and its criminal law group (professors [[Stephanos Bibas]], [[Leo Katz (jurist)|Leo Katz]], [[Stephen J. Morse]], [[Paul H. Robinson]], [[David Rudovsky]]). Some notable Penn Law faculty members include:\n\n[[File:Anita L Allen.JPG|thumb|Professor [[Anita L. Allen]]]]\n* [[Anita L. Allen]], deputy dean and privacy law and contemporary ethics \n* [[Tom Baker (professor)|Tom Baker]], deputy dean and insurance law \n* [[Stephanos Bibas]], criminal law scholar, current judge for the [[US Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Stephen B. Burbank]], civil procedure \n* [[Howard F. Chang]], economic analysis of law\n* [[Cary Coglianese]], government regulation and regulatory policy\n* [[Douglas Frenkel]], mediation and legal ethics\n* [[Geoffrey C. Hazard, Jr.]], legal ethics and civil procedure, former Director of the [[American Law Institute]] (1984\u20131999)\n* [[Leo Katz (jurist)|Leo Katz]], criminal law\n* [[Jonathan Klick]], empirical law and economics\n* [[Michael Knoll]], real estate and tax law\n* [[Charles W. Mooney Jr.|Charles (\"Chuck\") Mooney Jr.]], commercial law and bankruptcy law  \n*[[Curtis R. Reitz]], commercial law; Pennsylvania representative to the [[National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws]]\n* [[Dorothy E. Roberts]], race, gender, and the law\n* [[Kermit Roosevelt III|Kermit Roosevelt]], constitutional law scholar and novelist\n* [[David Rudovsky]], civil rights and criminal defense\n* [[Chris William Sanchirico]], tax policy, evidence, and tax law\n* [[Anthony Joseph Scirica]], current judge, and former chief judge, of the US Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit<ref name=blumenthal2013>{{Citation\n |author=Jeff Blumenthal |date=February 23, 2013 |title=Penn Law puts federal judge on faculty |periodical=[[Philadelphia Business Journal]] |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/news/2013/02/28/penn-law-puts-former-federal-judge-on.html |accessdate=March 1, 2013 }}</ref>\n* [[Amy Wax]], social welfare law and policy\n* [[Tobias Barrington Wolff]], civil procedure and constitutional law\n* [[Christopher Yoo]], law and technology\n\nThe School's faculty is complemented by renowned international visitors in the frames of the Bok Visiting International Professors Program. Past and present Bok professors include [[Juan Guzm\u00e1n Tapia]] (the first judge who prosecuted former Chilean dictator [[Augusto Pinochet]]), [[Armin von Bogdandy]] (Director at the [[Max Planck Institute]] for Comparative Public Law and International Law), [[Pratap Bhanu Mehta]] (President of the Centre for Policy Research in India), and [[Michael Trebilcock]] (Distinguished University Professor at the University of Toronto).\n\nSome of Penn's former faculty members have continued their careers at other institutions (''e.g.'', [[Bruce Ackerman]] (now at Yale),  [[Lani Guinier]] (now at Harvard),  [[Michael H. Schill]] (now at Oregon), [[Myron T. Steele]] (now at Virginia), and [[Elizabeth Warren]] (at Harvard until her election to the [[United States Senate]])).\n\n==Toll Public Interest Center==\nPenn was the first national law school to establish a mandatory [[pro bono]] program, and the first law school to win the [[American Bar Association]]'s Pro Bono Publico Award.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}  The public interest center was founded in 1989 and was renamed the Toll Public Interest Center in 2006 in acknowledgement of a $10 million gift from Robert Toll (Executive Chairman of the Board of [[Toll Brothers]]) and Jane Toll. In 2011 the Tolls donated an additional $2.5 million. The Toll Public Interest Center has supported many students who have won the [[Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom#Skadden Fellowship Foundation|Skadden Fellowship]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.skaddenfellowships.org/sitecontent.cfm?page=recentFellows |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117221137/http://www.skaddenfellowships.org/sitecontent.cfm?page=recentFellows |archive-date=2012-01-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> called by ''The Los Angeles Times'' \"a legal Peace Corps.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skaddenfellowships.org/sitecontent.cfm?page%3Dabout |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 8, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010181141/http://www.skaddenfellowships.org/sitecontent.cfm?page=about |archivedate=October 10, 2006 }} Skadden Fellowship Foundation: About the Foundation</ref>\n\nStudents complete 70 hours of pro bono service as a condition of graduation.  More than a third of the Class of 2009 substantially exceeded the requirement. Students can create their own placements, or select from 1,200 slots in 400 public interest organizations in Philadelphia and nationwide. The law school awards Toll Public Interest Scholarships to accomplished public interest matriculants, and has a generous Public Interest Loan Repayment Program for graduates pursuing careers in public interest. Students interested in public interest work receive funding for summer positions through money from the student-run Equal Justice Foundation or via funding from Penn Law.  Additionally, the law school funds students interested in working internationally through the International Human Rights Fellowship.\n\n==Center for Ethics and the Rule of Law==\nThe Center for Ethics and the Rule of Law (CERL or Center) is a non-partisan, interdisciplinary research and policy institute at the University of Pennsylvania. CERL focuses on the application of the rule of law and ethics to pressing issues of [[national security]], [[Veterans affairs|veterans' affairs]], [[War|armed conflict]], and [[International crisis|transnational crises]]. CERL was co-founded in 2012 by Professor [[Claire Finkelstein]], Algernon Biddle Professor of Law and Professor of Philosophy at the University of Pennsylvania Law School, and by William Craven, Chairman of Federal Systems and the Center's first Executive Board Chair, principally as a direct response to the interrogation policies and abuses in the post-9/11 era,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedp.com/article/2012/09/penn-law-unveils-center-for-ethics-and-the-rule-of-law|title=Penn Law unveils Center for Ethics and the Rule of Law|last=Bromfield|first=Heather|access-date=2017-09-25|language=en-us}}</ref> including at Baghdad's [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse|Abu Ghraib Prison]].\n\nThe central mission of CERL is to protect and promote rule of law values and ethical principles in the face of international challenges such as conflict with violent non-state actors, (seemingly) irrational and dangerous enemies, and transnational security risks. Its primary means of accomplishing this is to foster an exchange of ideas among academics, analysts, and practitioners regarding the interplay of rule of law/ethics and national and international security matters; to share the products of those discussions through published volumes or in open forums to raise public consciousness; and to prepare briefing papers and otherwise disseminate its views to educate policymakers as well as to impact public discussion.\n\nMuch of CERL's work to date has revolved around setting up two annual [[Round table (discussion)|roundtable]], interdisciplinary conferences that bring together scholars and practitioners to consult on critical global issues relating to national or international security and the rule of law. Articles authored for the conference are then compiled with other writings into published volumes by [[Oxford University Press]]. CERL's event topics have been wide-ranging and included The Ethics of Autonomous Weapons Systems (November 2014),<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://issuu.com/pennlawits/docs/cerl_annual_report_2014-2015|title=CERL Annual Report 2014-2015|last=|first=|date=|work=issuu|access-date=2017-09-25|pages=22\u201323|language=en}}</ref> Preventing and Treating the Invisible Wounds of War: Combat Trauma and Psychological Injury (December 2015), The Ethics of Negotiation in Armed Conflict (April 2016), Using Law to Fight Terror: Legal Approaches to Combating Violent Non-State Actors (September 2016), Preserving Art and Culture in Times of War (April 2017), and Foreign Interference with Democratic Institutions (April 2017). Events are generally held at Penn Law School, but sometimes at other Philadelphia-area venues, such as the [[National Constitution Center]], the [[Penn Museum]], and the Perry World House.\n\nNotable speakers or participants at these events have included: [[James Cartwright|General James \"Hoss\" Cartwright]] (a Four-Star General who served as Vice Chairman of the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] from August 2007 to August 2011), [[Haleh Esfandiari|Dr. Haleh Esfandiari]] (the Iranian-American Founding Director of the [[Woodrow Wilson Center]]'s Middle East Program), [[Dennis Ross|Ambassador Dennis Ross]] (Director of the State Department's Policy Planning Staff under President George W. Bush and Special Middle East Coordinator under President Bill Clinton), [[Irina Bokova]] (Bulgarian Director-General of UNESCO from 2009-2017), [[David E. Sanger|David Sanger]] (Chief White House Correspondent for ''The New York Times''), and General [[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]] (former Director of the CIA and Director of the NSA).\n\nCERL publications include: ''Targeted Killings: Law and Morality in an Asymmetrical World'' (OUP, April 2012),<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/targeted-killings-9780199646470|title=Targeted Killings: Law and Morality in an Asymmetrical World|date=2012-04-30|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199646470|location=Oxford, New York}}</ref> ''Cyberwar: Law and Ethics for Virtual Conflicts'' (OUP, May 2015),<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/cyber-war-9780198717508|title=Cyber War: Law and Ethics for Virtual Conflicts|date=2015-05-19|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198717508|location=Oxford, New York}}</ref> and ''Weighing Lives in War'' (OUP, October 2017).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/weighing-lives-in-war-9780198796176|title=Weighing Lives in War|date=2017-10-10|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198796176|location=Oxford, New York}}</ref> Several others are forthcoming based on prior CERL conferences: Sovereignty and the New Executive Authority, Ethical Dilemmas in the Global Defense Industry, The Ethics of Autonomous Weapons Systems, Preventing and Treating the Invisible Wounds of War: Combat Trauma and Psychological Injury, and The Ethics of Negotiation in Armed Conflict. CERL also issued its first policy briefing paper in January 2017, entitled, \"The Intersection of Opioid Usage and Veteran Mental Health Challenges.\"\n\nCERL's non-fiduciary Executive Board consists of a high-level mix of former U.S. government officials, law professors, philosophy professors, businesspersons, and practicing lawyers. The current Chair of the Executive Board is Paul G. Haaga, Jr., formerly the Chairman of the Board, Capital Research and Management Company and Vice Chair of National Public Radio (NPR).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/people/142208881/paul-haaga|title=Paul G. Haaga, Jr.|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref> CERL also benefits from advisory input from a roster of  experts drawn from the ranks of academia, the military, legal practice, and business, including [[Vijay Kumar (roboticist)|Vijay Kumar]], Dean of the Penn Engineering School;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kumarrobotics.org/|title=Vijay Kumar Lab|website=www.kumarrobotics.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref> Stuart Diamond, author of a best-selling book on negotiations;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2011/01/16/hardcover-advice/|title=Best Sellers - January 16, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and Jeff McMahan, Professor of Philosophy at the University of Oxford.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philosophy.ox.ac.uk/people/jeff-mcmahan|title=Jeff McMahan {{!}} Faculty of Philosophy|website=www.philosophy.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.upenn.edu/institutes/cerl/people.php|title=People \u2022 Penn Law|website=www.law.upenn.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25}}</ref> In March 2017, CERL hired its inaugural Executive Director, David A. Sadoff, who formerly served as Deputy Legal Adviser and Director for Intelligence Reform at the National Security Council (NSC), Assistant General Counsel at the CIA, and General Counsel to the International Development Law Organization (IDLO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cisdl.org/people/fellowship/david-a-sadoff.html|title=CISDL - David A. Sadoff|website=cisdl.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926042049/http://cisdl.org/people/fellowship/david-a-sadoff.html|archive-date=2017-09-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCERL is a not-for-profit that is supported financially by individual donors, corporations, foundations, other centers, institutes, and programs on and off the Penn campus, and by the Penn Law School and the University of Pennsylvania's Office of the Provost.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.law.upenn.edu}}\n\n{{Penn}}\n{{Law Schools of the Mid-Atlantic States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University Of Pennsylvania Law School}}\n[[Category:Law schools in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania, University of]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania Law School]]\n[[Category:1790 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania schools|Law School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox law school\n| name                  = University of Pennsylvania<br>Carey Law School\n| image                 =\n| image_size            = 250px\n| alt                   = University of Pennsylvania Carey Law School\n| caption               =\n| motto                 =\n| parent                = [[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| religious affiliation =\n| established           = {{Start date|1850}}\n| type                  = [[Private university|Private]] [[Law School]]\n| endowment             =\n| parent endowment      = $13.8 billion (June 30, 2018)<ref>[http://www.investments.upenn.edu/about-us About Us | Penn Office of Investments<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| dean                  = Theodore Ruger\n| city                  = 3501 Sansom Street, [[Philadelphia]]\n| state                 = Pennsylvania\n| country               = US\n| coordinates           = {{coord|39.953938|-75.192085|type:edu_globe:earth_region:US-PA|display=title,inline}}\n| students              = 755<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/university-of-pennsylvania-03140 \"University of Pennsylvania, #7 in Best Law Schools\"]</ref>\n| faculty               = 103<ref name=ABAData>[http://officialguide.lsac.org/SearchResults/SchoolPage_PDFs/ABA_LawSchoolData/ABA2926.pdf Penn Law School Official ABA Data] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126162122/http://officialguide.lsac.org/SearchResults/SchoolPage_PDFs/ABA_LawSchoolData/ABA2926.pdf |date=January 26, 2009 }}</ref>\n|ranking = 7<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings \"Best Law Schools\"]</ref>\n| bar pass rate         = 99.61% (2019)<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.law.upenn.edu/live/files/8594-penn-law-aba-bar-passage-report \"University of Pennsylvania Law School; Ultimate Bar Passage\"]</ref>\n| website               = {{URL|www.law.upenn.edu}}\n| aba profile           = [https://www.law.upenn.edu/live/files/5191-aba-509 \"Penn Law Profile\"]\n| logo                  =\n| logo_size             =\n| logo_alt              =\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Pennsylvania Carey Law School''' (formerly the '''University of Pennsylvania Law School''', sometimes shortened to '''Penn Law''', '''UPenn Law''', or '''Penn Carey Law''') is the law school of the [[University of Pennsylvania]], an [[Ivy League law schools|Ivy League]] university located in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]].  It is among the most selective and oldest law schools in the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.stanford.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/default/files/biblio/1002/145871/doc/slspublic/lomio_etal-rp20.pdf|title=Ranking of Top Law Schools 1987-2009 by US News & World Report|author1=J. Paul Lomio |author2=Erika V. Wayne |author3=George D. Wilson |last-author-amp=yes |date=July 5, 2016|work=US News & World Report|access-date=5 July 2016}}</ref> and is currently ranked 7th overall by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings |title=Best Law Schools |work=US News & World Report|date= |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> It offers the degrees of [[Juris Doctor]] (J.D.), [[Master of Laws]] (LL.M.), Master of Comparative Laws (LL.C.M.), Master in Law (M.L.), and [[Doctor of Juridical Science|Doctor of the Science of Law]] (S.J.D.).\n\nThe entering class typically consists of approximately 250 students, and admission is highly competitive.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">[https://www.law.upenn.edu/admissions/jd/entering-class-profile.php Admissions: Entering Class Profile \u2022 Penn Law<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Penn Law's July 2018 weighted first-time bar passage rate was 92.09%.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The law school is one of the [[Law school rankings in the United States#Top 14 law schools|\"T14\" law schools]], that is, schools that have consistently ranked within the top 14 law schools since ''U.S. News & World Report'' began publishing rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prelawhandbook.com/law_school_rankings__1987_1999 |title=Prelaw Handbook Historical US News Rankings |publisher=PRELAWHANDBOOK |date= |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> In the class entering in 2018, over half of students were women, over a third identified as persons of color, and 10% of students enrolled with an advanced degree.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nThe law school offers an extensive curriculum and hosts various student groups, research centers, and activities. Students publish the ''[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]]'', the oldest law journal in the country.<ref name=Almanac>[http://www.upenn.edu/almanac/v47/n12/LawTimeline.html \"University of Pennsylvania Law School Sesquicentennial History\"], University of Pennsylvania Almanac, accessed 15 Sep 2011</ref> Students also publish ''[[The Regulatory Review]]'', a regulatory news, analysis, and commentary that publishes daily.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=https://www.theregreview.org/about-us/|website=The Regulatory Review|accessdate=20 September 2017}}</ref> Among the school's alumni are a US Supreme Court Justice, several state Supreme Court Justices and supreme court justices of foreign countries, as well as several founders of law firms, university presidents and deans, business entrepreneurs, and politicians.\n\nBased on student survey responses, [[American Bar Association|ABA]], and [[NALP]] data, 99.2% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time employment after graduation, with a median salary of $180,000, as 76% of students joined law firms and 11% obtained judicial clerkships.<ref name=autogenerated3>[https://www.law.upenn.edu/careers/employment-statistics.php Careers: Employment Statistics \u2022 Penn Law<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The law school was ranked # 2 of all law schools nationwide by the ''[[National Law Journal]]'' in terms of sending the highest percentage of 2018 graduates to the 100 largest law firms in the US (60%).<ref name=\"nationallawjournal.com\">[https://www.law.com/2019/03/07/and-no-1-on-this-years-go-to-law-school-is/ \"Ranking The Go-To Law Schools,\" ''National Law Journal''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lewis 5333429670 112607c0ef o.jpg|thumb|180px|[[William Draper Lewis]], Penn Law's Dean, and founder of the [[American Law Institute]]]]\nThe University of Pennsylvania Law School, later University of Pennsylvania Carey Law School, traces its origins to a series of lectures delivered, in 1790, by [[James Wilson (justice)|James Wilson]], a signer of the [[United States Declaration of Independence]] and the [[United States Constitution]].<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/about/history/ |title=History of Penn Law |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> Penn began offering a full-time program in law in 1850, under the leadership of [[George Sharswood]].<ref name=\"history\" /> In 1852, Penn was the first law school in the nation to publish a law journal still in existence, then called ''The American Law Register'', which was later renamed the ''[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]]'', one of the most-cited law journals in the world.<ref name=\"lawlib.wlu.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://lawlib.wlu.edu/LJ/index.aspx|title=Law Journals: Submissions and Ranking|work=wlu.edu|access-date=2017-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060307221833/http://lawlib.wlu.edu/LJ/index.aspx|archive-date=2006-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Louis_Pollak.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Louis H. Pollak]], Dean and later a judge of the  [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania|US District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania]].]]\nIn 1881 the first woman was admitted to the school, [[Carrie Burnham Kilgore]], and in 1888 the first African American man graduated from the school, [[Aaron Albert Mossell]].<ref>[https://www.law.upenn.edu/about/history.php About: History \u2022 Penn Law<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[William Draper Lewis]] was named dean in 1896.<ref name=\"Almanac\"/> In 1900, the Trustees of the University of Pennsylvania approved a move to the law school's current location at the intersection of 34th and [[Chestnut Street (Philadelphia)|Chestnut Street]]s.<ref name=\"Owen Roberts 1949\">Owen Roberts, William Draper Lewis, 98 ''U. Pa. L. Rev.'' 1 (1949)</ref> Under Lewis' deanship, the law school was one of the first schools to emphasize legal teaching by full-time professors instead of practitioners, a system that is still followed today.<ref name=\"Owen Roberts 1949\"/> As legal education became more formalized, the school initiated a three-year curriculum and instituted stringent admissions requirements. While the School continued to accept students who did not hold a bachelor's degree, it warned applicants that \"[a] large number of those who study law are college graduates; and those who are not cannot hope, except in rare instances, to compete successfully with the college man.\"<ref>\"Department of Law,\" Catalogue of the University of Pennsylvania, 1899-1900 234 (1899).</ref>\n\nAfter 30 years with the law school, Lewis founded the [[American Law Institute]] in 1925, which was seated in the law school and was chaired by Lewis himself. The ALI was later chaired by another of Penn Law's Deans, [[Herbert Funk Goodrich]]. Two years before Goodrich was named dean, in 1927 the law school graduated with a J.D. [[Sadie Tanner Mossell Alexander]], who was the first African-American woman to ever receive a Ph.D. in the United States (also from the University of Pennsylvania, in economics).<ref name=Almanac/> The first woman to join the faculty was [[Martha Field]] in 1969; she is now a professor at [[Harvard Law School]].<ref name=Almanac/> From 1974 to 1978 the Dean of the law school was [[Louis Pollak]], who later became a federal judge.\n\nIn November 2019, Penn Law received a $125 million donation from the W.P. Carey Foundation, the largest single donation to any law school to date; the school was renamed University of Pennsylvania Carey Law School, in honor of the foundation's first president, Penn Law alumnus Francis J. Carey (1926-2014), who was the brother of [[William P. Carey|William Polk Carey]] (1930 - 2012), founder of the [[W. P. Carey|W. P. Carey Inc.]] [[REIT]], and of the charitable foundation.<ref>[https://www.thedp.com/article/2019/11/penn-law-carey-foundation-donation-renaming \"Penn Law renamed \u2018Carey Law School\u2019 following record $125 million donation\", by Manlu Liu, November 8, 2019. Retrieved November 17, 2019.]</ref><ref>[https://penntoday.upenn.edu/news/w-p-carey-foundation-makes-historic-125-million-gift-name-penns-law-school \"W. P. Carey Foundation makes historic $125 million gift to name Penn\u2019s law school\", by Steven Barnes, ''PennToday'', Office of University Communications, November 8, 2019. Retrieved November 17, 2019.]</ref> The change was met by some controversy, and a petition to quash the abbreviated \"Carey Law\", in favor of the traditional \"Penn Law\", was circulated.\n<ref>[http://www.nationaljurist.com/national-jurist-magazine/penn-laws-name-change-honor-big-donor-causing-outcry 'Penn Law's name change in honor of big donor is causing outcry\", by Mike Stetz, ''The National Jurist'']</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:University of Pennsylvania Law School-angled.JPG|300px|thumb|Silverman Hall]]\nThe University of Pennsylvania campus covers over 269 acres (~1&nbsp;km\u00b2) in a contiguous area of [[West Philadelphia]]'s [[University City, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|University City]] district. All of Penn's schools, including the law school, and most of its research institutes are located on this campus. Much of Penn's architecture was designed by the architecture firm of [[Cope & Stewardson]], whose principal architects combined the [[Gothic architecture]] of the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of Cambridge]] with the local landscape to establish the [[Collegiate Gothic]] style.\n\nThe law school consists of four interconnecting buildings around a central [[courtyard]].  At the east end of the courtyard is Silverman Hall, built in 1900, housing the Levy Conference Center, classrooms, faculty offices, the Gittis Center for Clinical Legal Studies, and administrative and student offices. Directly opposite is Tanenbaum Hall, home to the Biddle Law Library several law journals, administrative offices, and student spaces. The law library houses 1,053,824 volumes and volume equivalents making it the 4th-largest law library in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/university-of-pennsylvania-03140|title=University of Pennsylvania|work=rankingsandreviews.com}}</ref> Gittis Hall sits on the north side and has new classrooms (renovated in 2006) and new and expanded faculty offices.  Opposite is Golkin Hall, which contains {{convert|40000|sqft|m2}} and includes a state-of-the-art court room, 350-seat auditorium, seminar rooms, faculty and administrative offices, a two-story entry hall, and a roof-top garden.\n\nA small row of restaurants and shops faces the law school on Sansom Street.  Nearby are the Penn Bookstore, the Pottruck Center (a {{convert|115000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} multi-purpose sports activity area), the Institute of Contemporary Art, a performing arts center, and area shops.\n\n==Academics==\n\n===School orientation===\nFor the class entering in the fall of 2018, 14.6% out of 6,483 applicants were offered admission, with 249 matriculating. For the class entering in 2018 the 25th and 75th [[LSAT]] percentiles for the entering class were 164 and 171, respectively, with a median of 170.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> The 25th and 75th undergraduate [[GPA]] percentiles were 3.49 and 3.95, respectively, with a median of 3.89.<ref>https://www.law.upenn.edu/admissions/jd/entering-class-profile.php</ref><ref>https://www.ilrg.com/rankings/law/1/desc/Employ9Mos?name=&state=</ref>\n\nThroughout its modern history, Penn has been known for its strong focus on inter-disciplinary studies, a character that was shaped early on by Dean [[William Draper Lewis]].<ref>[[Margaret Center Klingelsmith]], \"History of the Department of Law of the University of Pennsylvania,\" The Proceedings at the Dediction of the New Building of the Department of Law, February 21st and 22nd, 1900, 16-18 (George Erasmus Nitzsche, comp. 1901).</ref> Its medium-size student body and the tight integration with the rest of Penn's schools (the \"One University Policy\")<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archives.upenn.edu/primdocs/uplan/paoneuniv1972.pdf |title=Pennsylvania: One University |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Archives |year=1973 |accessdate=2011-09-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120128081440/http://www.archives.upenn.edu/primdocs/uplan/paoneuniv1972.pdf |archive-date=2012-01-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> have been instrumental in achieving that aim. More than 50% of the law school's courses are interdisciplinary, and it offers more than 20 joint and dual degree programs, including a JD/MBA ([[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]]), a JD/PhD in Communication ([[Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania]]), and a JD/MD ([[Perelman School of Medicine at the University of Pennsylvania|Perelman School of Medicine]]).\n\nVarious certificate programs that can be completed within the 3-year JD program are also available, e.g. in Business and Public Policy (in conjunction with the [[Wharton School]]), in Cross-Sector Innovation (with the School of Social Policy & Practice), in International Business and Law (the Themis Joint Certificate with ESADE Law School, Barcelona, Spain), and in Social Cognitive and Affective Neuroscience (SCAN).<ref>{{cite web |title=SCAN Certificate helps law students use neuroscience to understand human behavior |url=https://www.law.upenn.edu/live/news/5382-scan-certificate-helps-law-students-use |website=Penn Law}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Graduate Certificate in Social, Cognitive & Affective Neuroscience (SCAN) |url=https://neuroethics.upenn.edu/scan/ |website=Center for Neuroscience and Society}}</ref> Nineteen percent of the Class of 2007 earned a Certificate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/crossdisc/study/certificates/ |title=Penn Law&nbsp;\u2013 Certificates of Study |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525174504/http://www.law.upenn.edu/crossdisc/study/certificates/ |archive-date=May 25, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Penn Law also offers joint degrees with international affiliates such as [[Sciences Po]] (France), [[ESADE]] (Spain), and the [[University of Hong Kong Faculty of Law]]. Under the guidance of former Dean Michael A. Fitts, the School has further expanded its international programs with the addition of the International Internship Program, the International Summer Human Rights Program, and the Global Research Seminar, all under the umbrella of the Penn Law Global Initiative. Penn Law takes part in a number of international annual events, such as the [[Monroe E. Price Media Law Moot Court Competition]] at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2011 International Rounds in Oxford&nbsp;\u2013 Results|url=http://pricemootcourt.socleg.ox.ac.uk/competitions/oxford/2011/results|publisher=University of Oxford&nbsp;\u2013 Price Media Law Moot Court Programme|accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Career prospects===\nPenn combines a strong tradition in public service with being one of the top feeders of law students to the most prestigious law firms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202483173162&slreturn=1&hbxlogin=1|title=LAW SCHOOLS REPORT|work=National Law Journal}}</ref> Penn Law was the first top-ranked law school to establish a mandatory pro bono requirement, and the first law school to win American Bar Association's Pro Bono Publico Award. Nevertheless, still about 75% of each graduating class enters private practice. In 2012, the law school placed more than 60% of its graduates into the United States' top 250 law firms, maintaining Penn's rank as the number one law school in the nation for the percentage of students securing employment at these top law firms.<ref name=\"National Law Journal law.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?interactive=true&id=1202543436520 |title=Ranking The Go-To Law Schools |work=National Law Journal|date= |accessdate= February 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202589189668&interactive=true National Law Journal law.com. Retrieved August 12, 2013.]</ref>\n\n===Journals===\nStudents at the law school publish several legal journals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/prospective/studentactivities.html |title=List of Student Activities |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525172052/http://www.law.upenn.edu/prospective/studentactivities.html |archive-date=May 25, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The flagship publication is the ''[[University of Pennsylvania Law Review]]'', the oldest [[law review]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pennumbra.com|title=University of Pennsylvania Law Review - PennLawReview.com|work=pennumbra.com}}</ref> Penn Law Review started in 1852 as the ''American Law Register'', and was renamed to its current title in 1908.<ref name=Almanac/> It is one of the most-cited law journals in the world,<ref name=\"lawlib.wlu.edu\"/> and one of the four journals that are responsible for ''[[The Bluebook]]'' (along with the Harvard, Yale, and Columbia law journals). ''Penn Law Review'' articles have captured seminal historical moments in the 19th and 20th century, such as the passage of the [[19th Amendment to the United States Constitution|19th Amendment]], the lawlessness of the first and second [[World War]], the rise of the civil rights movement, and the war in Vietnam.<ref>Edwin J. Greenlee, The University of Pennsylvania Law Review: 150 Years of History, 150 ''U. Pa. L. Rev.'' 1875 (2002)</ref>\n\nOther law journals include:\n*''[[University of Pennsylvania Journal of Constitutional Law]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pennjcl.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126053840/http://www.pennjcl.com/ |archive-date=2012-11-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> one of the top 50 law journals in the United States based on citations and impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lawlib.wlu.edu/LJ/index.aspx |title=Law Journals: Submissions and Ranking |publisher=Lawlib.wlu.edu |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060307221833/http://lawlib.wlu.edu/LJ/index.aspx |archive-date=March 7, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*''[[University of Pennsylvania Journal of International Law]]'', f/k/a ''Journal of International Economic Law'', f/k/a ''Journal of International Business Law'', f/k/a ''Journal of Comparative Business and Capital Market Law''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pennjil.com |title=The Journal of International Law |publisher=Pennjil.com |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n*''[[University of Pennsylvania Journal of Business Law]]'', f/k/a ''Journal of Business and Employment Law''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/journals/jbl/ |title=The University of Pennsylvania Journal of Business Law |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date=November 12, 2010 |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n*''[[University of Pennsylvania Journal of Law and Social Change]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.upenn.edu/journals/jlasc/ |title=The Journal of Law and Social Change |publisher=Law.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n*''[[East Asia Law Review]]'', f/k/a ''Chinese Law and Policy Review''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pennealr.com |title=East Asia Law Review&nbsp;\u2013 Journal of Law and Practice in East Asian Nations Including China, Japan, Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Macau, Tibet |publisher=Pennealr.com |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121165128/http://www.pennealr.com/ |archive-date=November 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==U.S. Supreme Court clerkships==\nSince 2000, Penn has had [[List of law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States|seven alumni]] serve as judicial clerks at the [[U.S. Supreme Court]]. This record gives Penn a ranking of 10th among all law schools for supplying such law clerks for the period 2000-2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bcgsearch.com/article/900047770/Law-Schools-That-Send-the-Most-Attorneys-to-United-States-Supreme-Court-Clerkships/ |title=Law Schools That Send the Most Attorneys to United States Supreme Court Clerkships |publisher=BCGSearch.com |date=2014-12-05 |accessdate=2019-11-29}}</ref> Penn has placed [[List of law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States|48 clerks]] at the U.S. Supreme Court in its history, ranked 11th among law schools; this group includes [[Curtis R. Reitz]], who is the [[Algernon Sydney Biddle]] Professor of Law, Emeritus at Penn.\n\n==Employment==\nBased on student survey responses, [[American Bar Association|ABA]], and [[NALP]] data, 99.2% of the Class of 2018 obtained full-time employment after graduation, with a median salary of $180,000, as 76% of students joined law firms and 11% obtained judicial clerkships.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nThe law school was ranked # 2 of all law schools nationwide by the ''[[National Law Journal]]'' in terms of sending the highest percentage of 2018 graduates to the largest 100 law firms in the US (60%).<ref name=\"nationallawjournal.com\"/>\n\n==Costs==\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition ($61,608), fees, and living expenses) for the 2018-2019 academic year was $95,400.<ref>[https://www.law.upenn.edu/admissions/grad/tuition-fees.php Graduate Programs: Tuition & Fees \u2022 Penn Law<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{main|List of Penn Law School alumni}}\n\n[[File:Jowenroberts.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Owen Roberts]], U.S. Supreme Court Justice]]\n\n===Judiciary===\n* [[Owen Roberts]], U.S. Supreme Court Justice \n* [[James Harry Covington]], Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of the District of Columbia]] \n* [[Daniel John Layton]], Chief Justice of the [[Delaware Supreme Court]] \n* [[Robert Nelson Cornelius Nix, Jr.]], Chief Justice of the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]]\n* [[Horace Stern]], Chief Justice of the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]]\n* [[George Sharswood]], Chief Justice of the [[Pennsylvania Supreme Court]]\n* [[Deborah Tobias Poritz]], Chief Justice of the [[New Jersey Supreme Court]]\n* [[Ayala Procaccia]], Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Israel]] \n* [[Ronald Wilson]], Justice of the [[High Court of Australia]]\n* [[Yvonne Mokgoro]], Justice of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]]\n* Jasper Yeates Brinton, the architect of the Egyptian court system, Justice of the Egyptian Supreme Court, and former U.S. Legal Advisor to Egypt \n* [[Arlin Adams]], Circuit Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Max Rosenn]], Circuit Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Dolores Sloviter]], Circut Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[James Hunter III]], Circut Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Patty Shwartz]], Circuit Judge of the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Phyllis Kravitch]], Senior Circuit Judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]]\n* [[Helene N. White]], Circuit judge on the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]]\n* [[Gerard Hogan]], Justice of the [[Court of Appeal (Ireland)|Court of Appeal of Ireland]]\n\n===Government===\n* [[George W. Wickersham]], Attorney General of the United States, 1909\u20131913; instrumental in the breakup of [[Standard Oil]]; President of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]] (1933\u201336)<ref>{{cite web|title=George W. Wickersham|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/384/000167880/|publisher=Notable Names Data Base|accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Philip Werner Amram]], Asst. Attorney General of the United States, 1939\u201342<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Emancipation: The Making of the Black Lawyer, 1844-1944|author1=Smith, J.C.|author2=Marshall, T.|date=1999|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press, Incorporated|isbn=9780812216851|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1lOIjQUG4aoC&pg=PA187|page=187|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Robert J. Walker]], U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, 1840\u201345<ref>{{cite web|title=Robert J. Walker|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000067|publisher=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[William M. Meredith]], U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, 1849\u201350\n*[[Jay Clayton (attorney)|Walter J. \"Jay\" Clayton III]], Chairman, U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, 2017 - present. <ref>https://www.sec.gov/news/press-release/2017-94</ref>\n* [[Josiah E. DuBois Jr.]], U.S. State Department official, instrumental in Holocaust rescue<ref name=\"google4\">{{cite book|title=Blowing the Whistle on Genocide: Josiah E. Dubois Jr., and the Struggle for a U.S. Response to the Holocaust|author1=Medoff, R.|author2=Wyman, D.S.|author3=Eizenstat, S.|author4=Morgenthau, H.|date=2009|publisher=Purdue University|isbn=9781557535078|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yV7taankpswC&pg=PA2|page=2|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas K. Finletter]], U.S Secretary of the Air Force, 1950\u20131953; Ambassador to NATO, 1961\u201365<ref name=\"google5\">{{cite book|title=Secretaries and chiefs of staff of the United States Air Force|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=9781428990463|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qLM3IGCLkywC&pg=PA19|page=19|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lindley Miller Garrison]], U.S. Secretary of War, 1913\u201316<ref name=\"google6\">{{cite book|title=The United States in the First World War: An Encyclopedia|author1=Venzon, A.C.|author2=Miles, P.L.|date=1999|publisher=Garland Pub.|isbn=9780815333531|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YiZRC8bsOuoC&pg=PA250|page=250|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[William B. Gray]], United States Attorney for Vermont, 1977-1981<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hr1964.org/obits.htm#Gray |title=Class of 1964 Obituaries: William Barton Gray |date=1994 |website=HR 1964.org |publisher=Harvard-Radcliffe Class of 1964 |location=Cambridge, MA |access-date=November 16, 2019 |ref={{sfnRef|\"Class of 1964 Obituaries: William Barton Gray\"}}}}</ref>\n* [[Earl G. Harrison]], Commissioner of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service, 1942\u201344{{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n* [[George Washington Woodruff]], Acting U.S. Secretary of the Interior under President Theodore Roosevelt<ref>{{cite web|title=George Washington Woodruff|url=http://www.archives.upenn.edu/people/1800s/woodruff_geo_w.html|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|accessdate=January 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423201641/http://www.archives.upenn.edu/people/1800s/woodruff_geo_w.html|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Heath Tarbert]] Nominee for Assistant Secretary of the Treasury for International Markets and Development in the U.S. (2017)<ref>https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/04/04/president-donald-j-trump-announces-intent-nominate-heath-p-tarbert</ref>\n* [[William H. Brown, III]], Chairman, [[EEOC]]<ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=National Journal|author1=Government Research Corporation|author2=Center for Political Research|author3=Government Research Company|date=1971|volume=3|publisher=Government Research Corporation|issn=0360-4217|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zLZVAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Gilbert F. Casellas]], Chairman, [[EEOC]] and [[General Counsel of the Air Force]]<ref>{{cite web|title=GILBERT F. CASELLAS|url=http://www.eeoc.gov/eeoc/history/35th/bios/gilcasellas.html|website=eeoc.gov|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph Sill Clark]], U.S. Senator from Pennsylvania and Mayor of Philadelphia\n* [[Charles Robert Miller]], Governor of Delaware \n* [[Charles A. Heimbold, Jr.]], U.S. Ambassador to Sweden and former Chairman and CEO of [[Bristol-Myers Squibb Company]]  \n* [[Raul Roco]], former presidential candidate and Secretary of Education in the Philippines \n* [[Oscar Goodman]], Mayor of [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]\n* [[Harry Arista Mackey]], Mayor of Philadelphia\n* [[Martin J. Silverstein]], U.S. Ambassador to Uruguay \n* [[Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky]], member of the U.S. House of Representatives and women's rights activist\n\n===Academia===\n* [[Mark Yudof]], President of the [[University of California]] system\n* [[Peter J. Liacouras]], Chancellor of [[Temple University]]\n* [[John Frederick Zeller III]], President of [[Bucknell University]]\n* [[Rodney K. Smith]], President of [[Southern Virginia University]]\n* [[Janice R. Bellace]], first president of Singapore Management University\n* [[Fred Hilmer]], Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of New South Wales]] \n* [[Robert Butkin]], Dean of the [[University of Tulsa College of Law]]\n* [[William Schnader]], drafter of the [[Uniform Commercial Code]] \n* [[William Draper Lewis]], founder of the [[American Law Institute]] and Dean of Penn Law\n* [[Henry Martyn Hoyt, Jr.]], [[Solicitor General of the United States]]\n* [[E. Grey Lewis]], General Counsel of the [[U.S. Navy]]\n* [[Anthony Amsterdam]], professor at [[New York University School of Law]]\n* [[Khaled Abou El Fadl]], professor of law at [[UCLA School of Law]]\n* [[Curtis Reitz]], the Algernon Sydney Biddle Professor of Law at the University of Pennsylvania Law School \n* [[Caroline Burnham Kilgore]], Penn Law's first female graduate (1883) \n* [[Sadie Tanner Mossell Alexander]], the first African-American woman to receive a Ph.D. in the U.S. and graduated from Penn Law in 1927\n\n===Private Practice===\n* [[James Harry Covington]], co-founder of international law firm [[Covington & Burling]]\n* [[George Wharton Pepper]], U.S. Senator from Pennsylvania, and founder of national law firm [[Pepper Hamilton]]\n* Russell Duane, co-founder of international law firm [[Duane Morris]] \n* Stephen Cozen, co-founder of international law firm [[Cozen O'Connor]]\n\n===Business===\n* [[Safra Catz]], CEO of [[Oracle Corporation]]\n* [[Henry Silverman]], CEO of [[Cendant Corporation]] \n* [[Scott Mead]], partner and managing director of [[Goldman Sachs]]\n* [[Peter Detkin]], co-founder of [[Intellectual Ventures]] and former Vice-President and assistant general counsel at [[Intel]]\n* [[Paul G. Haaga, Jr.|Paul Haaga]], Chairman of Capital Research and Management Company of the [[Capital Group Companies]])\n* [[Sam Hamadeh]], founder of [[Vault.com]]\n* [[Edward Benjamin Shils]], professor and founder of the first research center for entrepreneurial studies in the world, at the Wharton School\n* [[David L. Cohen]], former Chief of Staff to Philadelphia Mayor [[Ed Rendell]]\n* [[Gigi Sohn]], founder and President of [[Public Knowledge]]\n\n===Media and arts===\n* [[Renee Chenault-Fattah]], co-anchor of weekday edition of [[WCAU]] [[NBC]] 10 News in Philadelphia\n* [[Mark Haines]], host on [[CNBC]] television network \n* [[El McMeen]], guitarist \n* [[Norman Pearlstine]], editor-in-chief of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' \n* [[Lisa Scottoline]], author of [[legal thriller|legal thrillers]]\n* [[Moe Jaffe]], bandleader and songwriter\n* [[John Heisman]], namesake of the [[Heisman Trophy]], graduated from the law school in 1892<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archives.upenn.edu/people/1800s/heisman_john.html|title=John Heisman (1869 - 1936)|work=upenn.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Notable faculty==\nThe law school's faculty is selected to match its inter-disciplinary orientation. Seventy percent of the standing faculty hold advanced degrees beyond the JD, and more than a third hold secondary appointments in other departments at the university. The law school is well known for its corporate law group, with professors [[Jill Fisch]], [[Charles W. Mooney Jr.|Charles (\"Chuck\") Mooney Jr.]], [[David Skeel]], and [[Michael Wachter]] being regularly included among the best corporate and securities law scholars in the country.<ref>[http://www.professorbainbridge.com/professorbainbridgecom/2011/05/corporate-practice-commentators-top-10-corporate-securities-articles-for-2010.html \"Corporate Practice Commentator's \"Top 10\" Corporate & Securities Articles for 2010\"]</ref> The School has also built a strong reputation for its law and economics group (professors [[Howard F. Chang]], [[Tom Baker (professor)|Tom Baker]]) and its criminal law group (professors [[Stephanos Bibas]], [[Leo Katz (jurist)|Leo Katz]], [[Stephen J. Morse]], [[Paul H. Robinson]], [[David Rudovsky]]). Some notable Penn Law faculty members include:\n\n[[File:Anita L Allen.JPG|thumb|Professor [[Anita L. Allen]]]]\n* [[Anita L. Allen]], deputy dean and privacy law and contemporary ethics \n* [[Tom Baker (professor)|Tom Baker]], deputy dean and insurance law \n* [[Stephanos Bibas]], criminal law scholar, current judge for the [[US Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]]\n* [[Stephen B. Burbank]], civil procedure \n* [[Howard F. Chang]], economic analysis of law\n* [[Cary Coglianese]], government regulation and regulatory policy\n* [[Douglas Frenkel]], mediation and legal ethics\n* [[Geoffrey C. Hazard, Jr.]], legal ethics and civil procedure, former Director of the [[American Law Institute]] (1984\u20131999)\n* [[Leo Katz (jurist)|Leo Katz]], criminal law\n* [[Jonathan Klick]], empirical law and economics\n* [[Michael Knoll]], real estate and tax law\n* [[Charles W. Mooney Jr.|Charles (\"Chuck\") Mooney Jr.]], commercial law and bankruptcy law  \n*[[Curtis R. Reitz]], commercial law; Pennsylvania representative to the [[National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws]]\n* [[Dorothy E. Roberts]], race, gender, and the law\n* [[Kermit Roosevelt III|Kermit Roosevelt]], constitutional law scholar and novelist\n* [[David Rudovsky]], civil rights and criminal defense\n* [[Chris William Sanchirico]], tax policy, evidence, and tax law\n* [[Anthony Joseph Scirica]], current judge, and former chief judge, of the US Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit<ref name=blumenthal2013>{{Citation\n |author=Jeff Blumenthal |date=February 23, 2013 |title=Penn Law puts federal judge on faculty |periodical=[[Philadelphia Business Journal]] |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/news/2013/02/28/penn-law-puts-former-federal-judge-on.html |accessdate=March 1, 2013 }}</ref>\n* [[Amy Wax]], social welfare law and policy\n* [[Tobias Barrington Wolff]], civil procedure and constitutional law\n* [[Christopher Yoo]], law and technology\n\nThe School's faculty is complemented by renowned international visitors in the frames of the Bok Visiting International Professors Program. Past and present Bok professors include [[Juan Guzm\u00e1n Tapia]] (the first judge who prosecuted former Chilean dictator [[Augusto Pinochet]]), [[Armin von Bogdandy]] (Director at the [[Max Planck Institute]] for Comparative Public Law and International Law), [[Pratap Bhanu Mehta]] (President of the Centre for Policy Research in India), and [[Michael Trebilcock]] (Distinguished University Professor at the University of Toronto).\n\nSome of Penn's former faculty members have continued their careers at other institutions (''e.g.'', [[Bruce Ackerman]] (now at Yale),  [[Lani Guinier]] (now at Harvard),  [[Michael H. Schill]] (now at Oregon), [[Myron T. Steele]] (now at Virginia), and [[Elizabeth Warren]] (at Harvard until her election to the [[United States Senate]])).\n\n==Toll Public Interest Center==\nPenn was the first national law school to establish a mandatory [[pro bono]] program, and the first law school to win the [[American Bar Association]]'s Pro Bono Publico Award.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}  The public interest center was founded in 1989 and was renamed the Toll Public Interest Center in 2006 in acknowledgement of a $10 million gift from Robert Toll (Executive Chairman of the Board of [[Toll Brothers]]) and Jane Toll. In 2011 the Tolls donated an additional $2.5 million. The Toll Public Interest Center has supported many students who have won the [[Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom#Skadden Fellowship Foundation|Skadden Fellowship]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.skaddenfellowships.org/sitecontent.cfm?page=recentFellows |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117221137/http://www.skaddenfellowships.org/sitecontent.cfm?page=recentFellows |archive-date=2012-01-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> called by ''The Los Angeles Times'' \"a legal Peace Corps.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skaddenfellowships.org/sitecontent.cfm?page%3Dabout |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 8, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010181141/http://www.skaddenfellowships.org/sitecontent.cfm?page=about |archivedate=October 10, 2006 }} Skadden Fellowship Foundation: About the Foundation</ref>\n\nStudents complete 70 hours of pro bono service as a condition of graduation.  More than a third of the Class of 2009 substantially exceeded the requirement. Students can create their own placements, or select from 1,200 slots in 400 public interest organizations in Philadelphia and nationwide. The law school awards Toll Public Interest Scholarships to accomplished public interest matriculants, and has a generous Public Interest Loan Repayment Program for graduates pursuing careers in public interest. Students interested in public interest work receive funding for summer positions through money from the student-run Equal Justice Foundation or via funding from Penn Law.  Additionally, the law school funds students interested in working internationally through the International Human Rights Fellowship.\n\n==Center for Ethics and the Rule of Law==\nThe Center for Ethics and the Rule of Law (CERL or Center) is a non-partisan, interdisciplinary research and policy institute at the University of Pennsylvania. CERL focuses on the application of the rule of law and ethics to pressing issues of [[national security]], [[Veterans affairs|veterans' affairs]], [[War|armed conflict]], and [[International crisis|transnational crises]]. CERL was co-founded in 2012 by Professor [[Claire Finkelstein]], Algernon Biddle Professor of Law and Professor of Philosophy at the University of Pennsylvania Law School, and by William Craven, Chairman of Federal Systems and the Center's first Executive Board Chair, principally as a direct response to the interrogation policies and abuses in the post-9/11 era,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedp.com/article/2012/09/penn-law-unveils-center-for-ethics-and-the-rule-of-law|title=Penn Law unveils Center for Ethics and the Rule of Law|last=Bromfield|first=Heather|access-date=2017-09-25|language=en-us}}</ref> including at Baghdad's [[Abu Ghraib torture and prisoner abuse|Abu Ghraib Prison]].\n\nThe central mission of CERL is to protect and promote rule of law values and ethical principles in the face of international challenges such as conflict with violent non-state actors, (seemingly) irrational and dangerous enemies, and transnational security risks. Its primary means of accomplishing this is to foster an exchange of ideas among academics, analysts, and practitioners regarding the interplay of rule of law/ethics and national and international security matters; to share the products of those discussions through published volumes or in open forums to raise public consciousness; and to prepare briefing papers and otherwise disseminate its views to educate policymakers as well as to impact public discussion.\n\nMuch of CERL's work to date has revolved around setting up two annual [[Round table (discussion)|roundtable]], interdisciplinary conferences that bring together scholars and practitioners to consult on critical global issues relating to national or international security and the rule of law. Articles authored for the conference are then compiled with other writings into published volumes by [[Oxford University Press]]. CERL's event topics have been wide-ranging and included The Ethics of Autonomous Weapons Systems (November 2014),<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://issuu.com/pennlawits/docs/cerl_annual_report_2014-2015|title=CERL Annual Report 2014-2015|last=|first=|date=|work=issuu|access-date=2017-09-25|pages=22\u201323|language=en}}</ref> Preventing and Treating the Invisible Wounds of War: Combat Trauma and Psychological Injury (December 2015), The Ethics of Negotiation in Armed Conflict (April 2016), Using Law to Fight Terror: Legal Approaches to Combating Violent Non-State Actors (September 2016), Preserving Art and Culture in Times of War (April 2017), and Foreign Interference with Democratic Institutions (April 2017). Events are generally held at Penn Law School, but sometimes at other Philadelphia-area venues, such as the [[National Constitution Center]], the [[Penn Museum]], and the Perry World House.\n\nNotable speakers or participants at these events have included: [[James Cartwright|General James \"Hoss\" Cartwright]] (a Four-Star General who served as Vice Chairman of the [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] from August 2007 to August 2011), [[Haleh Esfandiari|Dr. Haleh Esfandiari]] (the Iranian-American Founding Director of the [[Woodrow Wilson Center]]'s Middle East Program), [[Dennis Ross|Ambassador Dennis Ross]] (Director of the State Department's Policy Planning Staff under President George W. Bush and Special Middle East Coordinator under President Bill Clinton), [[Irina Bokova]] (Bulgarian Director-General of UNESCO from 2009-2017), [[David E. Sanger|David Sanger]] (Chief White House Correspondent for ''The New York Times''), and General [[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]] (former Director of the CIA and Director of the NSA).\n\nCERL publications include: ''Targeted Killings: Law and Morality in an Asymmetrical World'' (OUP, April 2012),<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/targeted-killings-9780199646470|title=Targeted Killings: Law and Morality in an Asymmetrical World|date=2012-04-30|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199646470|location=Oxford, New York}}</ref> ''Cyberwar: Law and Ethics for Virtual Conflicts'' (OUP, May 2015),<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/cyber-war-9780198717508|title=Cyber War: Law and Ethics for Virtual Conflicts|date=2015-05-19|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198717508|location=Oxford, New York}}</ref> and ''Weighing Lives in War'' (OUP, October 2017).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/weighing-lives-in-war-9780198796176|title=Weighing Lives in War|date=2017-10-10|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780198796176|location=Oxford, New York}}</ref> Several others are forthcoming based on prior CERL conferences: Sovereignty and the New Executive Authority, Ethical Dilemmas in the Global Defense Industry, The Ethics of Autonomous Weapons Systems, Preventing and Treating the Invisible Wounds of War: Combat Trauma and Psychological Injury, and The Ethics of Negotiation in Armed Conflict. CERL also issued its first policy briefing paper in January 2017, entitled, \"The Intersection of Opioid Usage and Veteran Mental Health Challenges.\"\n\nCERL's non-fiduciary Executive Board consists of a high-level mix of former U.S. government officials, law professors, philosophy professors, businesspersons, and practicing lawyers. The current Chair of the Executive Board is Paul G. Haaga, Jr., formerly the Chairman of the Board, Capital Research and Management Company and Vice Chair of National Public Radio (NPR).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/people/142208881/paul-haaga|title=Paul G. Haaga, Jr.|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref> CERL also benefits from advisory input from a roster of  experts drawn from the ranks of academia, the military, legal practice, and business, including [[Vijay Kumar (roboticist)|Vijay Kumar]], Dean of the Penn Engineering School;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kumarrobotics.org/|title=Vijay Kumar Lab|website=www.kumarrobotics.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref> Stuart Diamond, author of a best-selling book on negotiations;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2011/01/16/hardcover-advice/|title=Best Sellers - January 16, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and Jeff McMahan, Professor of Philosophy at the University of Oxford.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philosophy.ox.ac.uk/people/jeff-mcmahan|title=Jeff McMahan {{!}} Faculty of Philosophy|website=www.philosophy.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.upenn.edu/institutes/cerl/people.php|title=People \u2022 Penn Law|website=www.law.upenn.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25}}</ref> In March 2017, CERL hired its inaugural Executive Director, David A. Sadoff, who formerly served as Deputy Legal Adviser and Director for Intelligence Reform at the National Security Council (NSC), Assistant General Counsel at the CIA, and General Counsel to the International Development Law Organization (IDLO).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cisdl.org/people/fellowship/david-a-sadoff.html|title=CISDL - David A. Sadoff|website=cisdl.org|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926042049/http://cisdl.org/people/fellowship/david-a-sadoff.html|archive-date=2017-09-26|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nCERL is a not-for-profit that is supported financially by individual donors, corporations, foundations, other centers, institutes, and programs on and off the Penn campus, and by the Penn Law School and the University of Pennsylvania's Office of the Provost.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.law.upenn.edu}}\n\n{{Penn}}\n{{Law Schools of the Mid-Atlantic States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University Of Pennsylvania Law School}}\n[[Category:Law schools in Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania, University of]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania Law School]]\n[[Category:1790 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania schools|Law School]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Pennsylvania_Law_School"}
